# React Component Patterns

## Component Structure and Organization

### Component Template Syntax

Use the following syntax to declare React components:

```tsx
interface MyComponentProps {
  foo: string;
  bar: string;
}

function MyComponent(props: MyComponentProps): ReactNode {
  const { foo, bar } = props;
  return `${foo} ${bar}`;
}
```

For any exported components, always export the accompanying props interface:

```tsx
export interface MyComponentProps {
  foo: string;
  bar: string;
}

export function MyComponent(props: MyComponentProps): ReactNode {
  const { foo, bar } = props;
  return `${foo} ${bar}`;
}
```

Always include the destructuring `props` assignment, even if the component has no props:

```tsx
interface MyComponentProps {}

function MyComponent(props: MyComponentProps): ReactNode {
  const {} = props;
  return null;
}
```

### Hoisted Function Declarations for Child Components

When creating reusable child components within a file, prefer hoisted function declarations at the foot of the file over inline components or arrow functions.

#### ✅ Preferred Pattern
```tsx
export interface ParentComponentProps {
  items: Array<{ id: string; title: string; description: string }>;
}

export function ParentComponent(props: ParentComponentProps): ReactNode {
  const { items } = props;
  return (
    <div>
      {items.map(({ id, title, description }) => (
        <ChildComponent key={id} title={title} description={description} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}

interface ChildComponentProps {
  title: string;
  description: string;
}

function ChildComponent(props: ChildComponentProps) {
  const { title, description } = props;
  return (
    <div>
      <h3>{title}</h3>
      <p>{description}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

#### ❌ Avoid These Patterns
```tsx
// Don't use inline components
export const ParentComponent = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <div>
        <h3>Title 1</h3>
        <p>Description 1</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>Title 2</h3>
        <p>Description 2</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

// Don't use arrow function components inside the main component
export const ParentComponent = () => {
  const ChildComponent = ({ title, description }) => (
    <div>
      <h3>{title}</h3>
      <p>{description}</p>
    </div>
  );

  return <div>{/* ... */}</div>;
};
```

## Component Refactoring Guidelines

### When to Extract Child Components

Extract repeated JSX patterns into child components when:
- The same structure is repeated 2+ times
- The pattern has configurable properties (props)
- The pattern represents a logical UI unit

### Prop Interface Design

Always define explicit TypeScript interfaces for component props:

```tsx
// ✅ Good: Explicit interface
interface ButtonProps {
  variant: 'primary' | 'secondary';
  size?: 'small' | 'medium' | 'large';
  disabled?: boolean;
  onClick: () => void;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

function Button(props: ButtonProps) {
  const { variant, size = 'medium', disabled = false, onClick, children } = props;
  // Implementation
}

// ❌ Avoid: Inline prop types
function Button({ variant, size, disabled, onClick, children }: {
  variant: 'primary' | 'secondary';
  size?: 'small' | 'medium' | 'large';
  disabled?: boolean;
  onClick: () => void;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}) {
  // Implementation
}
```

### Sequences of child elements

Depending on whether the sequence is generated from an extensible list, determine whether to use data-driven rendering or sequences of hardcoded static JSX child elements.

#### Extensible lists

For extensible lists of items, prefer data-driven rendering:

```tsx
// ✅ Good: Data-driven rendering
export function Navigation(props: NavigationProps): ReactNode {
  const {} = props;
  const NAVIGATION_ITEMS = [
    // Extensible set of items
    { label: 'Home', path: '/', icon: HomeIcon },
    { label: 'About', path: '/about', icon: InfoIcon },
    { label: 'Contact', path: '/contact', icon: ContactIcon },
  ];
  return (
    <nav>
      {NAVIGATION_ITEMS.map(({ path, label, icon }) => (
        <NavigationItem key={path} label={label} icon={icon} />
      ))}
    </nav>
  );
}

// ❌ Avoid: Hardcoded repetition
export function Navigation(props: NavigationProps): ReactNode {
  const {} = props;
  return (
    <nav>
      <NavigationItem label="Home" path="/" icon={HomeIcon} />
      <NavigationItem label="About" path="/about" icon={InfoIcon} />
      <NavigationItem label="Contact" path="/contact" icon={ContactIcon} />
    </nav>
  );
};
```

#### Static sequences

For static sequences with a fixed set of items, prefer hardcoded repetition:

```tsx
// ✅ Good: Hardcoded repetition
function ColumnLayout(props: ColumnLayoutProps): ReactNode {
  const { ribbon, sidebar, main } = props;
  return (
    <>
      <Column width={32}>{ribbon}</Column>
      <Column width={128}>{sidebar}</Column>
      <Column width={null}>{main}</Column>
    </>
  );
}

// ❌ Avoid: Data-driven rendering
export function ColumnLayout(props: ColumnLayoutProps): ReactNode {
  const { ribbon, sidebar, main } = props;
  const COLUMNS = [
    // Static set of items
    { id: 'ribbon', width: 32, children: ribbon },
    { id: 'sidebar', width: 128, children: sidebar },
    { id: 'main', width: null, children: main },
  ];
  return (
    <>
      {COLUMNS.map(({ id, width, children }) => (
        <Column key={id} width={width}>{children}</Column>
      ))}
    </>
  );
};
```

## Component Composition Patterns

### Container and Presentation Components

Separate logic from presentation:

```tsx
// Container component (handles logic)
export const UserListContainer = () => {
  const { users, loading, error } = useUsers();
  
  if (loading) return <LoadingSpinner />;
  if (error) return <ErrorMessage error={error} />;
  
  return <UserListPresentation users={users} />;
};

// Presentation component (handles UI)
interface UserListPresentationProps {
  users: User[];
}

function UserListPresentation({ users }: UserListPresentationProps) {
  return (
    <div>
      {users.map((user) => (
        <UserCard key={user.id} user={user} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Compound Components

For complex components with multiple related parts:

```tsx
export const Card = ({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) => (
  <div className="card">{children}</div>
);

function CardHeader({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return <div className="card-header">{children}</div>;
}

function CardBody({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return <div className="card-body">{children}</div>;
}

function CardFooter({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return <div className="card-footer">{children}</div>;
}

// Attach sub-components
Card.Header = CardHeader;
Card.Body = CardBody;
Card.Footer = CardFooter;
```

## Performance Considerations

### Memoization When Appropriate

Use React.memo for expensive pure components:

```tsx
import { memo, type ReactNode } from 'react';

interface ExpensiveComponentProps {
  data: ComplexData[];
  onAction: (id: string) => void;
}

const ExpensiveComponent = memo(function ExpensiveComponent(props: ExpensiveComponentProps): ReactNode {
  const { data, onAction } = props;
  // Expensive rendering logic
  return (
    <div>
      {data.map((item) => (
        <ComplexItem key={item.id} item={item} onAction={onAction} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
});
```

## Hook Conventions

### Minimize `useEffect` and `useRef` Usage

**Minimize use of `useEffect` and `useRef`, using only when absolutely necessary.** Prefer deterministic patterns such as `useMemo` and controlled components.

#### ✅ Preferred Patterns

```tsx
// ✅ Good: Use useMemo for derived values
export function AddressBook(props: UserListProps): ReactNode {
  const { users, filter } = props;
  
  const filteredUsers = useMemo(
    () => users.filter(user => user.name.includes(filter)),
    [users, filter],
  );
  
  return (
    <div>
      <UserList users={filteredUsers} />
    </div>
  );
}

// ✅ Good: Use controlled components instead of refs
export function SearchInput(props: SearchInputProps): ReactNode {
  const { value, onChange } = props;
  
  return (
    <input
      type="text"
      value={value}
      onChange={(e) => onChange(e.currentTarget.value)}
    />
  );
}

// ✅ Good: Use controlled components for form state
export function LoginForm(props: LoginFormProps): ReactNode {
  const { email, password, onEmailChange, onPasswordChange, onSubmit } = props;
  
  return (
    <form onSubmit={onSubmit}>
      <input
        type="email"
        value={email}
        onChange={(e) => onEmailChange(e.currentTarget.value)}
      />
      <input
        type="password"
        value={password}
        onChange={(e) => onPasswordChange(e.currentTarget.value)}
      />
      <button type="submit">Login</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

#### ❌ Avoid These Patterns

```tsx
// ❌ Avoid: Using useEffect for derived state
export function AddressBook(props: UserListProps): ReactNode {
  const { users, filter } = props;
  const [filteredUsers, setFilteredUsers] = useState<Array<User>>([]);
  
  useEffect(() => {
    setFilteredUsers(users.filter(user => user.name.includes(filter)));
  }, [users, filter]);
  
  return (
    <div>
      <UserList users={filteredUsers} />
    </div>
  );
}

// ❌ Avoid: Using refs for uncontrolled components when controlled is possible
export function SearchInput(props: SearchInputProps): ReactNode {
  const inputRef = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);
  
  const handleSubmit = () => {
    const value = inputRef.current?.value;
    // Use value...
  };
  
  return (
    <input
      ref={inputRef}
      type="text"
    />
  );
}
```


#### When `useEffect` is Acceptable

`useEffect` should only be used when:
- Setting up subscriptions to external systems (e.g., WebSocket connections, event listeners)
- Performing cleanup operations (e.g., unsubscribing, clearing timers)
- Integrating with imperative APIs (e.g., focusing elements, scrolling to positions)
- Synchronizing with external state that cannot be controlled via props

#### When `useRef` is Acceptable

`useRef` should only be used when:
- Storing mutable values that don't trigger re-renders (e.g., timer IDs, previous values for comparison)
- Accessing DOM elements for imperative operations (e.g., focusing, measuring, scrolling)
- Storing values that persist across renders but don't need to be in state

### `useEffect` Documentation Requirement

**Whenever adding a `useEffect`, ALWAYS precede it with an explanatory line comment describing the purpose of the effect.**

#### ✅ Required Pattern

```tsx
export function ChatWindow(props: ChatWindowProps): ReactNode {
  const { socket, roomId } = props;
  
  // Subscribe to WebSocket messages for the current room
  useEffect(() => {
    const handleMessage = (message: Message) => {
      // Handle message...
    };
    
    socket.on('message', handleMessage);
    
    return () => {
      socket.off('message', handleMessage);
    };
  }, [socket, roomId]);
  
  // Scroll to bottom when new messages arrive
  useEffect(() => {
    const chatContainer = document.getElementById('chat-container');
    if (chatContainer) {
      chatContainer.scrollTop = chatContainer.scrollHeight;
    }
  }, [props.messages]);
  
  return (
    <div id="chat-container">
      {/* Chat content */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

#### ❌ Avoid This Pattern

```tsx
export function ChatWindow(props: ChatWindowProps): ReactNode {
  const { socket, roomId } = props;
  
  useEffect(() => {
    const handleMessage = (message: Message) => {
      // Handle message...
    };
    
    socket.on('message', handleMessage);
    
    return () => {
      socket.off('message', handleMessage);
    };
  }, [socket, roomId]);
  
  useEffect(() => { // Missing comment explaining why this effect is needed
    const chatContainer = document.getElementById('chat-container');
    if (chatContainer) {
      chatContainer.scrollTop = chatContainer.scrollHeight;
    }
  }, [props.messages]);
  
  return (
    <div id="chat-container">
      {/* Chat content */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Testing Patterns

### Test Child Components Independently

```tsx
// Component file
export const ParentComponent = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <ChildComponent title="Test" description="Test description" />
    </div>
  );
};

interface ChildComponentProps {
  title: string;
  description: string;
}

export function ChildComponent({ title, description }: ChildComponentProps) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h3>{title}</h3>
      <p>{description}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

// Test file
import { ChildComponent } from './ParentComponent';

describe(ChildComponent, () => {
  it('renders title and description', () => {
    render(<ChildComponent title="Test Title" description="Test Description" />);
    
    expect(screen.getByText('Test Title')).toBeInTheDocument();
    expect(screen.getByText('Test Description')).toBeInTheDocument();
  });
});
```

## Component Test IDs

### Root Element Test IDs

All components that render a single intrinsic element (plain lowercase DOM element) as their root element **MUST** have a `data-testid` attribute assigned to this root element. The test ID should match the component name exactly.

```tsx
// ✅ Good: Root element has data-testid
export function Button(props: ButtonProps): ReactNode {
  const { children, onClick } = props;
  return (
    <button data-testid="Button" onClick={onClick}>
      {children}
    </button>
  );
}

// ✅ Good: Child component also has data-testid
export function Card(props: CardProps): ReactNode {
  const { children } = props;
  return (
    <div data-testid="Card">
      {children}
    </div>
  );
}

// ❌ Avoid: Missing data-testid on root element
export function Input(props: InputProps): ReactNode {
  const { value, onChange } = props;
  return (
    <input value={value} onChange={onChange} />
  );
}
```

### Child Component Test IDs

This rule also applies to child components declared within the same file as a parent component:

```tsx
export function UserProfile(props: UserProfileProps): ReactNode {
  const { user } = props;
  return (
    <div data-testid="UserProfile">
      <UserAvatar user={user} />
      <UserDetails user={user} />
    </div>
  );
}

// Child component in same file
interface UserAvatarProps {
  user: User;
}

function UserAvatar(props: UserAvatarProps): ReactNode {
  const { user } = props;
  return (
    <img 
      data-testid="UserAvatar" 
      src={user.avatarUrl} 
      alt={`${user.name}'s avatar`} 
    />
  );
}

// Another child component in same file
interface UserDetailsProps {
  user: User;
}

function UserDetails(props: UserDetailsProps): ReactNode {
  const { user } = props;
  return (
    <div data-testid="UserDetails">
      <h3>{user.name}</h3>
      <p>{user.email}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Nested Element Test IDs (Slots)

For more fine-grained identification of nested elements within a component's root element, use slot-based test IDs with the format `ComponentName:slot-name`:

```tsx
export function Modal(props: ModalProps): ReactNode {
  const { title, children, onClose } = props;
  return (
    <div data-testid="Modal">
      <div data-testid="Modal:header">
        <h2 data-testid="Modal:title">{title}</h2>
        <button data-testid="Modal:close-button" onClick={onClose}>
          ×
        </button>
      </div>
      <div data-testid="Modal:body">
        {children}
      </div>
      <div data-testid="Modal:footer">
        <button data-testid="Modal:cancel-button">Cancel</button>
        <button data-testid="Modal:confirm-button">Confirm</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Scroll pane IDs

All scrollable elements (i.e. elements with an `overflow` CSS style) must specify a `data-scroll-pane-id` attribute to identify the scrollable element. This is used to target the element when replaying user sessions.

The `data-scroll-pane-id` value uses the same format for nested slot element test IDs (i.e. `ComponentName:slot-name`), with a component's root element slot typically named `root`.

```tsx
export function ChatWindow(props: ChatWindowProps): ReactNode {
  return (
    <div
      data-testid="ChatWindow"
      data-scroll-pane-id="ChatWindow:root"
      style={{ overflow: "auto", height: 400 }}
    >
      {/* chat content */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

```tsx
export function Dashboard(props: DashboardProps): ReactNode {
  return (
    <div data-testid="Dashboard">
      <div
        data-scroll-pane-id="Dashboard:sidebar"
        style={{ overflowY: "auto", maxHeight: 300 }}
      >
        {/* sidebar content */}
      </div>
      <div>
        {/* main dashboard content */}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```


### Test ID Naming Convention

- **Root elements**: Use exact component name (`data-testid="Button"`)
- **Child components**: Use exact component name (`data-testid="UserAvatar"`)
- **Nested slots**: Use `ComponentName:slot-name` format (`data-testid="Modal:header"`)
- **Slot names**: Use kebab-case for multi-word slots (`data-testid="DataTable:sort-indicator"`)

### When to Use Test IDs

- **Always**: For components with single intrinsic root elements
- **Always**: For child components declared in the same file
- **Optional**: For complex nested elements that need specific testing
- **Never**: For styling purposes (use CSS classes instead)
- **Never**: For user-visible content (use proper semantic HTML instead)
